It was clear that the instructors are re-doing/re-using content from other lectures.

When this occurs, there are now new names for objects, accounts, OU's, etc and that makes it slightly more difficult to follow along. 

Also, as the course progressed, things started to get trimmed down.

The first few sections were very well developed and explained. As the sections went on, the explanations and content started to wane. For instance, for OS Deployment (a specific section I want to learn), the content was mostly PDF documents with extremely limited video content to support it.

I got through the course and was able to make everything work but there were definitely times that I had to remember what Item A was originally called (ex. Course started with ServerAcademy Site/OU. By the end, it was changed to ITFLEE or ITF and then somehow Chicago/New York OU's showed up). None of those were ever discussed prior.

In short, it has nothing to do with the 'preparation' itself. This is a very basic level course that barely touches upon topics that are advertised as 'covered'.

The instructor seems to be reading out of the paper behind the camera. Often he snaps and gets lost in the middle of the thought as if he tried to explain something using his own word but something clearly goes wrong in that process.

The Demos that are presented are way to short. The time split between demos and the 'presentation reading' is kept on the 20/80 ratio which is hillarious. If I wanted to hear a lector reading MSDN I would rather do it myself. Leaving alone the content that is presented - so basic yet instructor had troubles showing those basic ideas and often we ended up without doing what was told to be done leaving the concept unfinished.

There are WAY better courses available on Udemy and do not recommend this one. 

I wanted to point out this is not a RANT. I am not RUDE or UNRESPECTFUL for the time they put in this course. This is my humble opinon that might help some undecisive people out there wondering if this course is for them. I did not have this luxury and had to buy this one as it 'looked good' and the instructor 'seems to be credible'.

[{'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 45906565, 'content': "Some very interesting ideas. Not all of it was relevant. More geared to his stated target audience of 20 something males I thought, but I still appreciated the thinking behind it.

I liked the different perspective and ways of thinking about food and exercise. I was expecting to come across some fundamentalist thinking but didn't get it. There was stuff I disagreed with, but mostly because my situation is not the same I guess. 

The course was not just some regurgitated 4 hour body strategy, but showed some real thought about the emotional and motivational impact of food and exercise.

Some really useful takeaways like dealing with cravings and having backup plans for exercise and organizing around basic principles and frames", 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2020-02-19T17:55:34Z', 'modified': '2020-02-20T06:08:53Z', 'user_modified': '2020-02-19T18:03:38Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Kim Davis', 'name': 'Kim', 'display_name': 'Kim Davis'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 23934565, 'content': 'Helped me to look at my overall health and exercise habits from new and different perspectives and as a result I will be running a few "health" experiments to see how my body reacts to certain inputs.

'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Shalini P C', 'name': 'Shalini', 'display_name': 'Shalini P C'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 96815586, 'content': "There was some worthwhile content (which the instructor indicated was based on research, but neglected to mention which research).  I was particularly frustrated with the apparent lack of emotional intelligence from the instructor given that the course is literally about enhancing one's emotional intelligence.  There were some specific issues with the content.

Namely:
The course started off with a sort of note of warning, arrogantly dissing other courses as being not backed by data: dinged a half point.
The materials made a point to link conservative worldviews with xenophobia (see the disgust segment) based on an assumption of (as in, without providing evidence for) correlation between disgust and xenophobia: dinged another half point for bigotry/bias.
here was a generic reference to disgust sensitivity without any mention that there are many axes of it (e.g., some people are sensitive to smells, others to traditions, others to visual triggers, et cetera): dinged another half point.
The bias was embedded throughout the course (for example, references to traditions as outdated which were made in a manner that indicated disgust from the instructor): dinged another half point.
A recap should be at the end of a course, not in the middle, and it should be ten percent or less of the overall course runtime; the recap was 25% of the segment of the course it covered, and there was another segment after: dinged another half point.
Also, a recap should be a recap (covering the lesson bullet-point style, reserving the supporting information for the main presentation), not a re-hash (going into depth and detail): dinged another half point.
There were a lot of references to data without the identification of which studies resulted in the data: dinged another half point.
For the length of the course, I learned very little; it was definitely an ineffective use of my time: dinged another half point.

Positive bump-ups:
The standout part of the course is that the instructor responds in detail to some frequently asked questions; however, the answers did not necessarily address the question, even as posed by the instructor: extra half point.
Relevant clips from the marshmallow experiment were included, and the information was well integrated into the content: extra half point.", 'rating': 2.0, 'created': '2021-09-30T15:14:32Z', 'modified': '2021-10-01T16:05:54Z', 'user_modified': '2021-09-30T15:47:19Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Heather Johnston', 'name': 'Heather', 'display_name': 'Heather Johnston'}}]

I was expecting something boring and long, full of insiders terms. Instead, with my surprise, it was very light and clear, in a language that everyone can understand. The course covers also the basic on how to create a project in Kickstarter from scratch, starting from creating the project in the Kickstarter web page, and goes through several chapter covering the campaign life from the start to the end. There are also suggestions about the promotional videos, visit tracking, advertise the campaign with external sites, calculate costs and pledges . Each step is described and commented based on his experience of life in Kickstarter, and give the suggestions and trick to get outstanding results. There are a lot of precious informations and advices to avoid epic failures, that are based not only on theories, but are the results of the practical experience. The course was held by Richard Haberkern that had several outstanding successes in Kickstarter, and the style is like a one to one interview with him, and it is not boring at all. The course id divided in several short chapters where you should get only the key important facts, and has been removed any no added value info. The production quality is good, may be the background music is a little too high in some moments. If you are thinking to do a Kickstarter project take this course, it will help you to remove all the uncertainties you have as a beginners in Kickstarter.', 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2014-09-28T09:11:30Z', 'modified': '2014-09-28T16:11:30Z', 'user_modified': '2014-09-28T16:11:30Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Antimix', 'name': 'Antimix', 'display_name': 'Antimix'}}]

However,  I prefer courses that guide me creating the projects as well.  A lot of people learn by doing and I am one of them.  Also, I think he could have used more expression when teaching.  Even though the content was very good,  I started to fall asleep.  Finally,  I wondered if the "adobe spark"  logo could be removed from the pages like it is for the posts.  That question is important if we want to use our pages in our website.', 'rating': 4.0, 'created': '2018-03-03T14:42:51Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:23:07Z', 'user_modified': '2018-03-03T18:37:41Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Janis Friesler', 'name': 'Janis', 'display_name': 'Janis Friesler'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 11498452, 'content': "Excellent intro to Adobe Spark. I have only 2 reservations:

1)  I should have preferred an additional short lecture dealing purely with the possible 'next step' moves in any of the 3 programs.  I guess for young regular users of iphone, ipad or social media these may be obvious but these were the only comprehension issues I came across in the whole series of lectures. For instance different calls to action of the + sign - to create a new component, new page  etc ; when the forward arrow needs to be pressed - to play, replay etc. One way might be to list each of the move forward buttons and spell out how they are used - starting with the + sign and ending with 'Preview' and 'Share' or 'Download' This, I feel, would be a  useful overview reference.

The Second issue I partly addressed to you in an earlier email. You spend a great deal of time dealing with the choice of styles etc but when you are using photos you are extremely brief on Creative Commons and what sites Lightroom or Dropbox are and whether they offer royalty free photos. Not everyone in the class will be familiar with these and I guess Budget will be a key issue for those looking for specific photos. A brief guide to the range of options in price terms (for instance citing the quite expensive professional level Adobe Stock' you use at the top of the range' ) would be useful. Equally a brief explanation of how you can post a Spark Video to YouTube would be invaluable.

A few minor suggestions you might find useful 
- citing the facility of the rewind or a advance 15s and Speed box if wanted
- You mentioned Scrivenor but did not say what that is
- You mentioned Creative Cloud without explanation
- You mentioned Wordpress  - and usefully I do have a WP site - but for other learners maybe that needs a one sentence explanation. Presumably some doing the class have, or plan to have, non Wordpress sites

Other than these minor suggestions I found the course admirably clear and in the case of your wedding video an excellent example and charming (I have a Polish girlfriend).", 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2017-12-01T10:13:33Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:19:11Z', 'user_modified': '2017-12-01T18:46:33Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': "Anton D'Abreu", 'name': 'Anton', 'display_name': "Anton D'Abreu"}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 9830540, 'content': '', 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2017-09-26T20:51:05Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:16:36Z', 'user_modified': '2017-10-02T03:57:12Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Ikiara Kenneth Kirimi', 'name': 'Ikiara Kenneth', 'display_name': 'Ikiara Kenneth Kirimi'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 9825042, 'content': "Show don't tell is a phrase this course author has apparently never come across.", 'rating': 0.5, 'created': '2017-09-26T14:45:15Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:16:49Z', 'user_modified': '2017-09-26T14:45:15Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Beth Felice', 'name': 'Beth', 'display_name': 'Beth Felice'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 6796112, 'content': '', 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2017-05-06T07:35:49Z', 'modified': '2017-05-06T14:35:49Z', 'user_modified': '2017-05-06T14:35:49Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Stanislava Yordanova Stoyanova', 'name': 'Stanislava Yordanova', 'display_name': 'Stanislava Yordanova Stoyanova'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 4270380, 'content': 'Informationally, this proposes good tools. [{'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 78576994, 'content': "Mr. Adil has taken the trouble to touch on every aspects of the topic relating to youtube making, including you youtube SEO concepts. I have yet to totally apply all the concepts that he has taught us in this video course. Steele'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 197904, 'content': 'Only 5 of the 26 lectures fall into the security category. they include akismit, limit login, set new users as subscribers and backup and restore the database. 
All the work is done on an existing database no mention changing the database prefix, nothing about protecting hotlinking and no htaccess.
FTP was used already logged in so no mention of securing the link, using site manager or specialised accounts to block off outsiders.
Its a long course - over 4 hrs and I found myself drifting off because he seemed to leap about a lot.
The main thing I remember was when he was creating a password and he could not create a strong one of the top of his head e.g. Thisis/not4me!     Rule At least 1uc, 1lc, 1 number and 1 symbol and more than 8 characters and not in dictionary.  At the very least he could have suggested a generator site.', 'rating': 3.0, 'created': '2014-08-10T15:13:00Z', 'modified': '2014-08-10T22:13:00Z', 'user_modified': '2014-08-10T22:13:00Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Rosie Harrison', 'name': 'Rosie', 'display_name': 'Rosie Harrison'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 164572, 'content': "This course is for the wordpress beginner, looking to secure their wordpress installation. 1) The diagrams could be more useful if they would only follow what he is talking about. He will enter commands without identifying on the diagram where he is working.
2) The biggest problem I have is I feel this is one big troubleshooting session rather than teaching important points. So, there are mistakes made (which he does correct BUT valuable time is taken as he works through the problem). Why can't the videos be edited to cut out the troubleshooting stuff? Why can't the labs be set up prior to shooting the videos because he ends up going through this stuff so fast that I cannot follow the reasoning. Very frustrating! I am about done watching as there are better production efforts out there that will not waste my time.
3) Finished this course and still rate it three stars. The Private VLAN portion was the best of all as it was very informative, correct, and he did not spend a lot of time troubleshooting issues with his VMWare or network.
4) Unfortunately he spent A LOT of time in Lessons 62 and 63 troubleshooting his VMWare. It kind of pissed me off since I wanted to be taught, not watch him troubleshoot.
5) There were some inane statements made such as in Lesson 63 where he states "Static means what it means". C'mon, what a stupid comment!!
6) Finally, there were some outright mistakes made both on his slides and as he spoke which caused confusion, especially if you are not well-versed in the subject. For instance, in Lesson 59 a slide states that HSRP is defined by RFC 2338 when in fact that is the RFC for VRRP. HSRP is defined by RFC 2281. There are also numerous spelling errors on his slides, too numerous to outline here. 
Clearly there was very little, if any, QA done on this course which very much detracted from its value, as if the instructor did not really care if it was accurate or not. As such, I will not be purchasing any more of his courses in the future. 'Constance Roberts'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 26892302, 'content': "Real world application, very well organized, good for absolute beginners as well as seasoned pros, in-depth explanations that are not only logical but connect with the viewers in a meaningful way. Great take aways and many great exercises you can jump into right away.

I've been journaling all my life and I'm a professional storyteller and facilitator. Even with my experience I've learned so much about journaling in just the first section of this course.

The first section is a little less than an hour long, has seven sections, a well organized summary, and the power point presentations as course materials. The course could have ended there and I would still be pleased with this course. I can't wait to explore the rest of the course in the upcomming weeks.

The instructor is professional, engaging, straight to the point, and connects personally through the presentation. I love that Dr. Phalime uses a mixture of video and slide presentations.

It's a great course as is but if I were to make some suggests:

He is educational and gives the student the tools that he or she needs to successfully buy a car, but he does it without placing sales people as your enemy. I took a course before that portraited salespeople as your opponent, and I didn't like that because salespeople are necessary; they play a role in the process and if they're good they can be extremely helpful. 

I also liked that gives tools and steps to do before approaching a dealership which is conducive to a much better car acquiring experience. 

Overall the course was very comprehensive and complete, and I feel satisfied with the material taught. 

It wasn't clear to me how to get the invoice pricing, but then again, I don't know how much Best Buy bought a TV for when I buy it, and business do need to make profit to exist, so I guess that what really matters is to get a fair price and save money, while making it a win-win situation for all parties involved.

I recommend the course, it is a small investment that can save you thousands of dollars. With that said, I think that if you expect to purchase a car for 3% or 5% of dealer true-cost, it is going to be challenging and it is possible that a dealership won't take your offer. It is just my opinion based on what I have seen, but if you can get that deal, even better!

Take the course, there is nothing to lose and a lot to gain.

Sebastian", 'rating': 4.5, 'created': '2018-08-27T22:11:36Z', 'modified': '2018-08-28T19:02:11Z', 'user_modified': '2018-08-27T22:28:45Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Sebastian Alongi', 'name': 'Sebastian', 'display_name': 'Sebastian Alongi'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 19496542, 'content': '', 'rating': 4.0, 'created': '2018-08-09T18:58:35Z', 'modified': '2018-08-10T09:01:12Z', 'user_modified': '2018-08-09T18:58:37Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Lindsey Carr Jr.', 'name': 'Lindsey', 'display_name': 'Lindsey Carr Jr.'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 13680136, 'content': '', 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2018-02-11T16:19:27Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:22:13Z', 'user_modified': '2018-02-11T19:24:21Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Jeed', 'name': 'Jeed', 'display_name': 'Jeed'}}, {'_class': 'course_review', 'id': 13059124, 'content': '', 'rating': 5.0, 'created': '2018-01-23T16:29:18Z', 'modified': '2018-05-22T15:21:28Z', 'user_modified': '2018-01-24T11:59:11Z', 'user': {'_class': 'user', 'title': 'Reuven Uchitel', 'name': 'Reuven', 'display_name': 'Reuven Uchitel'}}]

The visual slides chosen as companions for the delivery of the lecture are  cleverly connected to the message going on, with the intention to help anchor its substance. A few statistical references place in real world the impact of email writing in business. 
I dare to suggest to all those who take the class and arrive at the end of it  content: have your children or significant others benefit, too! I doubt a high school teacher would design a worksheet that could come close to this, not because he/she could not, but because the educator is in reasoning in a different paradigm. I even foresee course takers who would pay a premium price for this class by not sharing the account, but by paying the premium price for value when registering a family member -  as if it had happened in real classroom setting. If we do the math in the US, the full price matches the cost of an average tutoring session.
